1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:11,000
You ready sir?

3
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:14,000
Sure. Great question I can be.

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:22,000
All right. Well good morning today is December 15th, 2015. This is David Klein from the History Department at Virginia Tech.

5
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:26,000
Also working with the Southern oral history program at UNC Chapel here. Hill.

6
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:32,000
And we are here this morning as part of the Civil Rights History Project of the Library of Congress.

7
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:38,000
This Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Southern oral history program.

8
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:42,000
And I have the great honor of being with General Julius Bechtung this morning.

9
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:47,000
And if you could just introduce yourself and this is the only time I'll script you at all.

10
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:52,000
A full sentence to start with I am or that my name is.

11
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:57,000
I'm Julius Wesley Bechtung Jr. Lieutenant General United States Army Richard.

12
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:59,000
Thank you. Happy.

13
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Thank you sir.

14
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:08,000
So let's just if we start with the where you are born and raised in a little bit about your family.

15
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,000
And then we'll have a conversation and take it from that.

16
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Okay. I was born in Brinmore, Pennsylvania.

17
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:21,000
I went to high school in Lower Marrying in high school. I just point that out because there are a few rather prominent graduates of Lower Marrying.

18
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:34,000
The Library of Congress has an example of Jim Billington, Al Hague of some notoriety, Hap Arnold, the former Commander of the Air Force, the former Air Corps.

19
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:45,000
If you live here in Washington, the anchor on Channel 4 is a graduate of Lower Marrying.

20
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:48,000
And we have other some prominent citizens.

21
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:52,000
Kobe Bryant, some people have never heard of him.

22
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:55,000
I understand he's retiring this year.

23
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,000
So we have that kind of program.

24
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:01,000
We have some outstanding academics at one time.

25
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:06,000
Lower Marrying was in the top 10 of the high schools in the country and they're still very hard now.

26
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:09,000
And they have a great reputation.

27
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:12,000
I'm happy to say that I get out of that place.

28
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
It will.

29
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
And this is what they call the main line.

30
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:18,000
The main line to fill it off you.

31
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:23,000
It's supposed to be, not supposed to be, is it very gritty and well to do.

32
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:28,000
I was born there because my father was a janitor in the department.

33
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,000
And we lived in the basement of the department.

34
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,000
And it's a block and a half from Brinmore College.

35
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:44,000
And two blocks from Brinmore Trees station that goes out from Philadelphia.

36
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:50,000
It's a very other schools, Rolls-Mount, Villanova, Kavrford, Swapwood,

37
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:53,000
just some of the schools that are in that area.

38
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:56,000
So they grew up in an academic field.

39
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:57,000
Right.

40
00:02:57,000 --> 00:03:05,000
And what were the sort of restraints or boundaries of race and class in that area as you were growing up?

41
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:10,000
It was part of the segregation areas.

42
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,000
However, the schools were not segregated.

43
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:18,000
We could not go into certain restaurants or could not.

44
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,000
We go to the theater.

45
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
We were required to sit down in front rows.

46
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:28,000
And if there were fill, we just, depending on how much the field would feel,

47
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,000
the film would be going.

48
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:34,000
We could remember, Mangle with Red the Folk, they wouldn't complain about it.

49
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,000
But it was segregated.

50
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:42,000
We're talking now back in the 20s and 30s.

51
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:46,000
It took some time to get through all of those things.

52
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:49,000
And so you had your high school years there.

53
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:53,000
And high school years, the Lord of Marys located in Arbor, Pennsylvania.

54
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:56,000
It's a township.

55
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,000
There were very few things we could not do.

56
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:05,000
We could not participate in the swimming program.

57
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:11,000
I do not remember in the four years I was in high school, county, ninth grade,

58
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,000
having gone to a prom.

59
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:15,000
It wasn't encouraged.

60
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:18,000
So we did not bother doing it.

61
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,000
We did not have to work in the four schools.

62
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:23,000
We were concerned academically.

63
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:25,000
We were encouraged to do the best we could.

64
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:28,000
I happen to have been a member of the student council.

65
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:31,000
The president of my class.

66
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:35,000
We started kindergarten together and he'll be invited to my birthday party.

67
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:36,000
We go back that four.

68
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Wonderful.

69
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:45,000
So after high school, after high school, I joined the Army Air Corps listed reserves

70
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:49,000
and I was a senior at Lord of Married.

71
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:55,000
And when I graduated, I came on to do the, what year was this?

72
00:04:55,000 --> 00:05:03,000
1944 when I came on to do the, my first duty station was the Luxe Mississippi,

73
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:05,000
T-Street Air Force Base.

74
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:13,000
As I sometimes say with tongue and cheek, I greet a place for young black 18 years old to go to in those times.

75
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:22,000
And taking the physical examination for flight school, I flunked the ice test.

76
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,000
I had stigmatism.

77
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:25,000
I knew I had that problem.

78
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:34,000
But when I walked into my testing in every other place, they had a big chart in a wall, big E, and then scale down.

79
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:38,000
And those days I could take one look at that chart and I had it memorized.

80
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,000
Front back either way.

81
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:44,000
They said, okay, cover your right eye, cover your right eye.

82
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:46,000
Cover the left eye, fine.

83
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:50,000
I got down a Keesler field, new machine, technology.

84
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:58,000
In a darkened room with a machine right back here, and you walk in, I don't see any chart.

85
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Room dark.

86
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,000
They pushed a button.

87
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
The chart comes up.

88
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:05,000
I had no chance.

89
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:08,000
I flunked the test.

90
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:18,000
And that sent me off to McDillfield, which was an Army Aviation Facility Engineer.

91
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:22,000
What had you been hoping you might be able to do?

92
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:27,000
I wanted to become a pilot in what turned out to be a Tuskegee Airman.

93
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Didn't have that name when I was there.

94
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:36,000
I wanted to become a pilot because half-barnal had come out to our high school and convinced us

95
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:40,000
to join the Army Air Corps when you're civil-winging and goal bars.

96
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And I got out, I went down, and after he finished his spiel, about half the football team went down to take the battery of tests.

97
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Six of us passed.

98
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:03,000
And on the 28th of December, 1943, we were all inducted into the Army Air Corps and let's the reserves.

99
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:09,000
And that's how I got into the flight program in the first place.

100
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:16,000
After going through Newcoma, Newcoma-Landwood with the reception station, I went to a Kiesler field.

101
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:20,000
My five other buddies went to Florida.

102
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:24,000
Kiesler went ahead, black Americans, to Florida, they did not have.

103
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:31,000
And so I might add that none of us became pilots for various reasons.

104
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:40,000
After that, off the McDeal field, Army Engineering.

105
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:46,000
Well, let me ask first, you said it tongue in cheek, blocks you not the best place perhaps to be.

106
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:50,000
Could you tell us a little bit about what conditions were there?

107
00:07:50,000 --> 00:08:02,000
For example, the one weekend I took off, we leave from Kiesler field, the buddy of mine, and I went down to Kiesler,

108
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:06,000
to Biluxy, rather, from the base.

109
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:12,000
And while walking down the street, we heard some noise coming from the rear.

110
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:14,000
There are two of them.

111
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:18,000
And we turned around here, and the pickup truck coming down to payment, driving at us.

112
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:23,000
We flat the guest walls, and they went by.

113
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:27,000
And we thought it may be a good idea to get back on post.

114
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
And so we did.

115
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:32,000
And that was typical treatment, treatment.

116
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:38,000
And I pointed out because many years later, I went back to Biluxy.

117
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:41,000
I am now a Lieutenant General United States Army.

118
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:46,000
I was invited back by the National Guard of Mississippi.

119
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:49,000
I was greeted by the Agent General.

120
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:56,000
I flew in in my own aircraft, the Army's aircraft, rather, which I control.

121
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:59,000
I was greeted by this AG.

122
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:10,000
We went from the airfield to a small camp that they had, and I forget to name it, a base, the Army of the Camp, rather.

123
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:20,000
I spent the night there, and then we drove to the hotel where they had a meeting of National Guard,

124
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:24,000
and reservists, for which I was to speak to.

125
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:29,000
And my first comment, my health, things have changed.

126
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:31,000
And I explained what I was talking about.

127
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:34,000
The last time I was down here, let me tell you what happened to me.

128
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:37,000
And of course, all of them knew and understood what I was exactly talking about.

129
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:48,000
I had a State Trooper escort from the airport to this camp, to the hotel, left in great fashion.

130
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,000
But that wasn't a significant change.

131
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:57,000
Still is not the best at a time, but it would help a lot better than when I was first there.

132
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:00,000
What were the barracks like in 1944?

133
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:04,000
It wouldn't build, wouldn't buildings, two story.

134
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:10,000
Just like everyone else, but we were separated from the rest of the post.

135
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:15,000
Control by the camp.

136
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:21,000
My company commander was a white, first lieutenant.

137
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:27,000
He had a white, exec, and the rest were black.

138
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:31,000
First Sergeant, the rest of the cadres.

139
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:38,000
As a matter of fact, it was there after I got down to McDill,

140
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:44,000
one of the engineering, aviation engineering unit.

141
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:49,000
And with the same setup, basically, structure.

142
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:56,000
The first Sergeant had been, was told by a public exec, that he's hurt,

143
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:03,000
that there was an announcement for, application of OCS.

144
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:07,000
And that fellow back to I understand was an aviation cadet.

145
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:10,000
He might be interested.

146
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:14,000
But at that time, I had become the first Sergeant's clerk.

147
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:16,000
How did I become his clerk?

148
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:19,000
One very wet day.

149
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:23,000
The first Sergeant came out and said, okay.

150
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:24,000
I need a clerk.

151
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:25,000
I need a volunteer.

152
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:26,000
Who can type?

153
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:29,000
I had typing as a club from a hand up.

154
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Okay, come here.

155
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:33,000
Let's go in.

156
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:36,000
Went into the first Sergeant's office.

157
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:39,000
I found out that the first Sergeant had a little problem.

158
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:45,000
My job was to read the company roster to him, the company roster,

159
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:48,000
because he could not read.

160
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:52,000
And he had it memorized, basically.

161
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:56,000
He would get up in front of the company and put that paper up and call the role.

162
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:57,000
That's a fewer reading.

163
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:01,000
That's the kind of Army we had at that time.

164
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:06,000
And because I was able to type and help him, you're my clerk.

165
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:09,000
Yes, first Sergeant.

166
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:13,000
And when his lieutenant came back from post, he said, there's a roster.

167
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:19,000
There's a campaign or statement on a board, vote and board at post,

168
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:24,000
that it could be an OCS application board.

169
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:26,000
You might, be sure it might be interested.

170
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:32,000
First Sergeant came in and said, you're going to go down and take a test.

171
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:35,000
You're going to go down and appear at board.

172
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:37,000
Yes, first Sergeant.

173
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:39,000
I went down.

174
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,000
And this is one of the weird things.

175
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:48,000
The President of the board had been through the township of Lormarion.

176
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:53,000
And when I mentioned that I had gone to Lormarion, played football there,

177
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:56,000
I had at least one person on my side.

178
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:02,000
I didn't do poorly, but that made me feel pretty good when I was trying to answer the questions.

179
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:08,000
That's how I started my process out of Tisler, out of Baluxy,

180
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:11,000
out of McDill Field.

181
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:18,000
And I passed the OCS test, passed the board.

182
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:33,000
And in January of 45, I went off to Fort Benning, infantry OCS.

183
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:36,000
I got there in these semis, in fact, in 1944.

184
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:39,000
School started in January of 45.

185
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:46,000
And I graduated from OCS in August of 45.

186
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:48,000
15 August in Marifold.

187
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:54,000
In the interesting part, they had dropped a bomb.

188
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:58,000
We were destined to go off to become infantry lieutenants.

189
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:08,000
And Marifold, when Germany quit about April of 45,

190
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:11,000
we started getting concerned because, hey, they might cut off OCS,

191
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:13,000
and there was no job.

192
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
We were on key OCS going.

193
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:19,000
As a result, when the Japanese dropped it, they said, well, we're just close.

194
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:21,000
They wouldn't there cut out OCS now.

195
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:30,000
They didn't, and we graduated on 16 August of 45.

196
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:40,000
I was sent off briefly to Alabama from basic training, duty.

197
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:46,000
And within three weeks, I was off to Pacific.

198
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:47,000
Well, yeah.

199
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:50,000
Now, OCS is sort of a quirk.

200
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:52,000
OCS is not, we're not segregated, correct?

201
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,000
No, Officer Kennedy School.

202
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:55,000
Right.

203
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:56,000
And they had Officer Kennedy School.

204
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:01,000
And it's designed to fill these void when they drop off sufficient,

205
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:05,000
not going to the official officers coming out of West Point,

206
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:09,000
or ROTCs, and there's still a need for more officers,

207
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:11,000
Officer Kennedy School to group that they turned to.

208
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:12,000
Right.

209
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:14,000
And that was an integrated.

210
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:15,000
That was integrated.

211
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:16,000
Yeah.

212
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:17,000
Yeah.

213
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:20,000
When I got there, integrated to a point.

214
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:22,000
You always have to make sure that you're clear.

215
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:26,000
I got inside the Officer Kennedy Regiment.

216
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:29,000
We were just like everyone on every other soldier.

217
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:33,000
Our training, we lived in integrated billets.

218
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:36,000
We can integrate everything.

219
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:40,000
However, you step outside of that regiment ever.

220
00:15:40,000 --> 00:15:42,000
You're back to the south.

221
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:46,000
You waited in your line to get on a certain bus.

222
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:50,000
Even there going to the theater, outside the region area.

223
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:57,000
You set a different location in your fellow candidates.

224
00:15:57,000 --> 00:16:02,000
But inside the training itself, completely integrated.

225
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:05,000
And were there service clubs on the base?

226
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:07,000
Yes, service clubs in the base.

227
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:09,000
But we went to a black service club.

228
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:12,000
And my white counterparts went to the white service club.

229
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:14,000
Same thing for the Officer, Officer Club.

230
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:21,000
And it was the southern way of doing business.

231
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:22,000
Okay.

232
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:24,000
So what then off to the Pacific?

233
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:27,000
Off to the Pacific, joined a 93rd Infantry Division.

234
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:34,000
All black divisions except for the division commander and his T-staff.

235
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:37,000
One of the more interesting parts about that.

236
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:42,000
We would overseas on a, well fortunately back up a little bit.

237
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:54,000
Before leaving the States, I went to a place staging area in California.

238
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:56,000
And I'm grouping now for the name of it.

239
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:02,000
But it was the place to go from that staging area overseas.

240
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:07,000
I met a couple of, or about 15 of us officers.

241
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:10,000
Two of them were Westponders.

242
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:18,000
And we became very good friends while we're in route to the Pacific.

243
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:24,000
So much so that they convinced me doing our transit.

244
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:27,000
If I ever had chance to go to Westpoint, I wouldn't do it.

245
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:28,000
Or I had my commission.

246
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:31,000
And I was not about to go through what they had to go through.

247
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:35,000
The sourcing treatment and the other things.

248
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:39,000
They also taught me how to shoot crap.

249
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:42,000
They took my money because they taught me how to shoot crap on a blanket.

250
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:45,000
If you know anything about shooting crap, that's the last thing you want to do.

251
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:47,000
And they took my money from that.

252
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:51,000
And I reminded them of that later when I had a chance.

253
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:54,000
Went off to the Pacific.

254
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:55,000
The war just over.

255
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:00,000
But there still were, I went to a place called Moritai, which is Southfoot,

256
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:03,000
the Philippine, North of New Guinea.

257
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:06,000
There were two divisions on Moritai.

258
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:08,000
The 93rd Division and the Diction Division.

259
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:10,000
Why the Army put those two divisions together?

260
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:11,000
I'll never know.

261
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:13,000
I tried to find out since then.

262
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:16,000
No one has given me a satisfactory answer.

263
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:22,000
But during the fighting, they did very well against the bad guy, the Japanese.

264
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:24,000
Keeped his mind as a war not going on.

265
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:26,000
We're fighting the Japanese.

266
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:33,000
When there were no fighting going on with the Japanese, they fought each other.

267
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:38,000
So much so that I was pulled out of my regiment.

268
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:44,000
I was in C Company, first battalion, three-sixth in Infantry,

269
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:54,000
and sent on detail to the Poes Marshall and the Diction Division had a lieutenant come up,

270
00:18:54,000 --> 00:19:02,000
and we rode patrols together to try to make sure maintain a little bit of peace.

271
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:03,000
Peace between the two.

272
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:06,000
Keep in mind, I was 19-year-old, second lieutenant.

273
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:12,000
This guy from Diction Division, the same age I was, so we were two characters stuck out there.

274
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:13,000
Driving around in a Jeep.

275
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:15,000
To drive around and keep peace.

276
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:16,000
Another interesting situation.

277
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:20,000
The Diction Division flying Confederate flags and all your things like this.

278
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:27,000
Confederate flag as well, regimental flag.

279
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:36,000
One of my combat activities was required to take a patrol into the hills,

280
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:40,000
and the new to Japanese were someplace up in the hills, up in the mountain.

281
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:43,000
The war was over, so we had Japanese translator.

282
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:48,000
We went out, I had my platoon.

283
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:54,000
The Japanese translator had a bullhorn, announcing the fact that war is over, give up,

284
00:19:54,000 --> 00:19:57,000
come on, we'll take care of you.

285
00:19:57,000 --> 00:20:01,000
For that, we got shot at, and we were told not to engage.

286
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:04,000
We had weapons to protect ourselves, but do not engage.

287
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:10,000
We got shot at, we knew where they were, came back, report that to the battalion commander.

288
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:17,000
He in turn reports that the regiment commander said, hey, no, the New York commander said,

289
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:21,000
they're up there, we know where they are, we'll just start them out.

290
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:27,000
That took her my first combat experience being shot at.

291
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:39,000
That went on for time to deactivate the division, January of 46.

292
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:46,000
If you had a certain number of quality points, or overseas points, you came home.

293
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:50,000
I did not have any of those things, I just got in there.

294
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:55,000
I, in the field, felt the respect to the technical services.

295
00:20:55,000 --> 00:21:01,000
I went to Manila as a signal unit.

296
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:06,000
I reported in company.

297
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:13,000
There were six officers, company commanders are captain.

298
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:21,000
I went to junior, Lieutenant of the Chemical Command was an infantry officer.

299
00:21:21,000 --> 00:21:27,000
The three officers were signal officers, and rest of them were infantry.

300
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:34,000
This is a heavy construction company, the kind of company that goes out and put them overhead wire and cable.

301
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:41,000
Jolder holes in the ground, put into holes, and then string cable.

302
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:47,000
I never drilled, I never been in a signal unit before, but one very much difficult.

303
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:49,000
I knew what I had to do.

304
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:54,000
I had a platoon of 30 odd soldiers.

305
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:03,000
All of them were signal officers, signal soldiers, and they were happy to get a youngster in that could help them with many things.

306
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:10,000
So they taught me how to climb holes, how to go up there, hang wire.

307
00:22:10,000 --> 00:22:15,000
We drilled a lot, I taught them how to do that.

308
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:18,000
I did something the other lieutenants would not do.

309
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:20,000
I climbed a pole and checked it out.

310
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:31,000
We had a chance on one occasion to put in poles for, we're talking now Manila for radio or commercial.

311
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:33,000
Radio of televisions too.

312
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:36,000
We put in 100 foot poles.

313
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:41,000
You put in 100 foot poles, you got about 10 feet into the ground.

314
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:47,000
Once you get the pole to ground, now you have to go up and hang the wire.

315
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:51,000
I didn't have much choice to go up or stay down.

316
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:55,000
My soldier up hanging wire, I'm going to climb a pole too.

317
00:22:55,000 --> 00:22:58,000
I have never, I don't like heights.

318
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:02,000
I got up that pole, went to the top of it.

319
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:06,000
Sold what they were doing and came back down.

320
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:14,000
Now, if you know anything about pole climbing, pole climbing, if you do 10 to 4 or slip,

321
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:17,000
the last thing you want to do is grab.

322
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:23,000
You push yourself away from the pole and you have gaps on your feet and shoes,

323
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:28,000
which forces you fit into the pole and keeps you from falling.

324
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:32,000
My other lieutenant wouldn't go up.

325
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:36,000
My part too was so happy, moving to the company, he said, my lieutenant does that.

326
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:38,000
Look at him.

327
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:43,000
Well, I went up once, have not been up that high again on the pole.

328
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:45,000
What I proved I could do it.

329
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:48,000
And that's the way we operated.

330
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:57,000
The company commander, as I said, was an infantry captain who later ran across in other services.

331
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:03,000
My tour there ended when I was reached at going home,

332
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:14,000
separated in 46, came home, went to,

333
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:19,000
I stayed in reserves, although I could have been separated.

334
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:23,000
If I just felt like what I was doing, I stayed in reserves.

335
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:30,000
In order to do that, I had to become a signal officer because I was infantry transferred to signal corps,

336
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:37,000
doing an assignment, and when the reserve went into signal officer.

337
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:43,000
State acted in the reserves and went to reserve training.

338
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:46,000
I had a chance to go to college.

339
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:48,000
Mine you had no college at this time.

340
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:53,000
I had a role in Lincoln University in Oxford, Pennsylvania, Lincoln College, excuse me.

341
00:24:53,000 --> 00:25:02,000
And at the week that I was supposed to report for class, which would have been in February of 47,

342
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:06,000
I got a call from my whole football coach, Laura Marion.

343
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:09,000
How would you like to go to Muleenberg?

344
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:11,000
We're in the health Muleenberg.

345
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:13,000
So now in town, Pennsylvania, why Muleenberg?

346
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:15,000
They got an excellent pre-med program.

347
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:20,000
I went to the doctor at that time, and I said, hmm, okay.

348
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:22,000
Sure.

349
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:26,000
And so I went to Muleenberg College.

350
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:29,000
At first, black American had gone to Muleenberg.

351
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:36,000
I was on a football scholarship, and I used to collect about $38 a month stipend.

352
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:40,000
We still care of my internals.

353
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:48,000
So you, so rather than go to Lincoln, which is next BCU, maybe the first thing to see you.

354
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:50,000
I went to Muleenberg.

355
00:25:50,000 --> 00:25:56,000
In Allentown, for black student, did very well as a matter of fact.

356
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:58,000
How were, let me back up a little bit.

357
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:06,000
Muleenberg, this is, I went there in February of 57, excuse me, 47.

358
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:10,000
And the coach at Muleenberg had just gotten there.

359
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:16,000
He came from a prep program, prep school, and he brought a couple of the old players,

360
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:19,000
and they were really good players.

361
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:25,000
He had spring practice, and we're out there under the lights, spring practice, contact.

362
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:30,000
You know, injured myself, my shoulders, part of the reason I injured myself,

363
00:26:30,000 --> 00:26:36,000
and how it happened, my equipment was not properly fitted.

364
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:41,000
The trainers who gave me equipment, that gave me inappropriate equipment,

365
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:45,000
and I suffered shoulder separation.

366
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:47,000
They purposely gave that to you.

367
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:52,000
I also understand, that's why I ended up getting it, this is what it went.

368
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:56,000
And I couldn't play football anymore.

369
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:03,000
And I decided then that I really don't need this because I was doing quite well academically.

370
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:08,000
And I found out that I could stay in college.

371
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:11,000
I was there on the GI Bill of Rights, so I didn't need to, Monday for that standpoint.

372
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:16,000
I didn't need to $30, $31 for stip for insininels.

373
00:27:16,000 --> 00:27:23,000
So I just dropped my scholarship, football scholarship, and got a series of upplaying academics.

374
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:29,000
Of course, I forgot to mention, between the time I got home, they went to Mulebert.

375
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:34,000
I met a young nurse from Severnfield, of the Uofia.

376
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:41,000
She was in nursing training, and we decided to get married.

377
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:50,000
So in 48, January of 48, 29th of January, 48, we had our wedding.

378
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:58,000
I'll point out that morning, day before that, I had taken a final exam in analytical geometry.

379
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:05,000
I'm a pre-med student, and I did not do well.

380
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:13,000
As a matter of fact, I went into that test, I read the questions, re-read them.

381
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:19,000
In my answer on the street, I wrote down, re-wrote the question, and took a guess on each question,

382
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:24,000
and turned in, and the professors called me and said,

383
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:29,000
you know you didn't do well.

384
00:28:29,000 --> 00:28:33,000
Yes, sir. I know exactly what you've done.

385
00:28:33,000 --> 00:28:38,000
You have been memorizing formulas, analytical geometry, and he's right.

386
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:43,000
I've been memorizing, not understanding it.

387
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:45,000
Up until that time, I've been doing quite well.

388
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:49,000
He said, okay, you've been making A's, but I'm going to give you a B,

389
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:53,000
but of course, because you've flown the final exam.

390
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:55,000
Yes, sir. I understand that.

391
00:28:55,000 --> 00:28:58,000
The very next day I had my wedding.

392
00:28:58,000 --> 00:29:02,000
And a lot of friends say, I know you've flown the test.

393
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:04,000
You're getting married.

394
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:06,000
So that makes a long story short.

395
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:14,000
We got married in 29th of January, and started off on our honeymoon,

396
00:29:14,000 --> 00:29:17,000
and on, we just had a great time.

397
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:22,000
I might add to honor honeymoon, which is a rather unique story.

398
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:28,000
My brother, who, younger than I, but had dropped out of school during World War II,

399
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:35,000
joined the Navy, frustrated his parents, and everyone else.

400
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:39,000
But he had dropped, he ran away from home a couple of times,

401
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:43,000
so mom was convinced that he would not do well staying there.

402
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:45,000
So he went to join the Navy.

403
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:47,000
She approved him to join the Navy.

404
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:50,000
And he went off going off to college.

405
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:57,000
And he was going to college and show you the rest of you in North Carolina.

406
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:01,000
To get down there, we were driving down.

407
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:07,000
And so my mother drove the car, and my brother Joe, my wife Louise,

408
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:08,000
and I went down.

409
00:30:08,000 --> 00:30:09,000
A unique story.

410
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:15,000
Your mother going on your honeymoon, but that's the way we operate in those days.

411
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:22,000
And dropped the more, came back up, and everything went fine from then.

412
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:34,000
But that was in January of 48.

413
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:37,000
State did quite well in school.

414
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:47,000
Harry Truman, later that year, issued the executive order 9981 to integrate the military.

415
00:30:47,000 --> 00:30:52,000
I really had enjoyed being in the military, and I was in training camp

416
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:58,000
that everything improving ground during the summer when the order was issued.

417
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:03,000
And I came back home and told my wife, well, I'll have a chance to go back to the actor duty.

418
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:06,000
And I really liked what I was doing.

419
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:08,000
And I could not be a doctor any hell.

420
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:14,000
I wasn't doing well in chemistry, which not very good for a doctor.

421
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:18,000
So she was happy to satisfy with because she was a nurse working.

422
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:22,000
So we weren't going to starve.

423
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:25,000
While I was at Aberdeen Proving Ground when the order was issued,

424
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:30,000
the commander of the post called all the officers together.

425
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:35,000
He read the executive order signed by the president.

426
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:40,000
And after he finished, and Aberdeen body was a completely integrated post,

427
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:43,000
read the executive order.

428
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:45,000
He called the duty officer.

429
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:48,000
And he said, as long as I'm here, there'd be no change.

430
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:52,000
And by that, he meant officer club number one, officer club number two.

431
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:56,000
Swimming pool number one, swim pool number two, NCO club number one, NCO club number two.

432
00:31:56,000 --> 00:31:59,000
All the ones are white, all the two are black.

433
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:05,000
And doing his very, as the commander, after the orders issued, no change.

434
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:14,000
So when I went back on act of duty, we were expecting our first child.

435
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:25,000
I was now at, I was on orders to a signal unit, signal unit at Fort Bliss Texas.

436
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:33,000
I was recalled as an infantry officer because I wanted to go to infantry.

437
00:32:33,000 --> 00:32:37,000
Part of my interruption, but I just wanted to follow up.

438
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:42,000
Having heard the president's executive order,

439
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:51,000
and I imagine having some reaction to that and hope for a career possibility is opening up.

440
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:55,000
And then hearing the response of the commander, the post commander,

441
00:32:55,000 --> 00:32:59,000
can you walk me through the range of feelings that you went through?

442
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:03,000
Well, let me back up a little bit of history.

443
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:07,000
World War I.

444
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:14,000
The black soldiers were fighting in segregated units.

445
00:33:14,000 --> 00:33:20,000
The commander and Europe, parsing did not want black troops.

446
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:24,000
Black Command.

447
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:34,000
So, $369 by unit in World War II had fought with the French because they preferred, they wanted us.

448
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:36,000
And it will.

449
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:41,000
Came back well rewarded.

450
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:45,000
And when a $369 got back in the States, they were not greeted as heroes,

451
00:33:45,000 --> 00:33:49,000
but they came back through New York and jeered.

452
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:54,000
In 1925, I could be off by a year.

453
00:33:54,000 --> 00:33:59,000
There was a study done at Carlisle Barrett, the Army War College,

454
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:06,000
basically saying that the black soldiers, while they may be good,

455
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:09,000
doing steeper-daw work,

456
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:14,000
laboring, they were not good for

457
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:22,000
thinking through a project or being able to officially control soldiers

458
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:26,000
and could not do certain other things, technical things.

459
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:29,000
That study stayed around for a long time.

460
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:35,000
So, when World War II came along, that was the mentality of the officer corps,

461
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:37,000
of leadership, of the war department.

462
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:40,000
There was no reason to change it.

463
00:34:40,000 --> 00:34:45,000
When B.O. Davis became a fighter pilot, he had some major problems,

464
00:34:45,000 --> 00:34:51,000
but because in 1993, the 99 pursuit squadron did very well.

465
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:54,000
We were able to shoot down aircraft and not lost any aircraft,

466
00:34:54,000 --> 00:35:00,000
not lost a fighter that day were escorting, or a permanent escorting.

467
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:05,000
So, it didn't surprise me or anyone else that there were certain beliefs

468
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:09,000
in the military, leaders that, not just the president, that we can do,

469
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:12,000
this is our Army, and we're gonna do what we wanna do.

470
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:18,000
May I point out today in 2015,

471
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:21,000
you have attitudes where folks are saying one thing,

472
00:35:21,000 --> 00:35:23,000
and the president is saying something else?

